{"id":14881410,"mediaExerciseId":"5970b619-c1ea-4e7a-8dbb-eb571e31a3d0","exerciseName":"11","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":453,"solutions":[{"id":5997087,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to determine portfolio betas. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **beta** indicates the volatility compared to the overall market. This is the predicted degree of change over securities for a 1% change in market portfolio expected excess.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first identify the given amounts in the problem: \n\n\n| | Amount$\\hspace{5pt}$| \n|:--|--:| \n|Portfolio weights: ||\n|Stock Q |20%|\n|Stock R |30%|\n|Stock S |35%|\n|Stock T|15%|\n|Security betas: ||\n|Stock Q| 0.79|\n|Stock R |1.23|\n|Stock S| 1.13|\n|Stock T| 1.36|\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/cfce299dc3902dd57f9a089363875dd4/lateximg_large.png","width":773},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/cfce299dc3902dd57f9a089363875dd4/lateximg.png","width":387}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The portfolio beta is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Porfolio beta}&=\\sum_{\\text{}}{\\text{Portfolio weight $\\times$ Security beta}}\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let us insert the provided data to the formula from step 4. As an illustration, here's what it looks like: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Porfolio beta}&={\\text{(20\\% $\\times$ 0.79) + (30\\% $\\times$ 1.23) + (35\\% $\\times$ 1.13) + (15\\% $\\times$1.36)}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":136,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/65d0f6fc3607bffabb5bf704bc972b0b/lateximg_large.png","width":1020},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/65d0f6fc3607bffabb5bf704bc972b0b/lateximg.png","width":509}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let us compute the portfolios's beta. This is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Porfolio beta}&={\\text{(20\\% $\\times$ 0.79) + (30\\% $\\times$ 1.23) + (35\\% $\\times$ 1.13) + (15\\% $\\times$1.36)}}\\\\\n\n&={\\text{0.158 + 0.369 + 0.3955 + 0.204}}\\\\\n\n&={\\textbf{1.1265}}\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":108,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/7c80af868b576df23c353faa39db2554/lateximg_large.png","width":843},"regular":{"height":56,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/7c80af868b576df23c353faa39db2554/lateximg.png","width":422}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"**To conclude, the portfolio's beta is 1.1265.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":173,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/67233bc68c7f89dc11844936dd073ad3/lateximg_large.png","width":1064},"regular":{"height":88,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6b7b45ba02f14b1b059b5a428bd1dbbb/67233bc68c7f89dc11844936dd073ad3/lateximg.